# Supabase — Production Readiness Checklist

Run every item on this list before you deploy a Rocket project to production.
These are the items that cause real incidents — not theoretical risks.

---

## The Official Supabase Production Checklist

### Security (must complete)

**1. Run Security Advisor**
```
Dashboard → Advisors → Security Advisor
Fix EVERY item flagged. No exceptions.
Flagged items include: tables without RLS, SECURITY DEFINER functions without search_path,
weak password policies, excessive extension privileges.
```

**2. Enable SSL Enforcement** *(off by default)*
```
Dashboard → Database → Settings → SSL Configuration → Enforce SSL → Enable

Or via CLI:
supabase ssl-enforcement update --project-ref [REF] --enable-db-ssl-enforcement

What this does: forces all direct Postgres connections (Drizzle, Prisma, psql) to use SSL.
HTTP APIs (PostgREST, Auth, Storage) already enforce SSL — this only affects direct DB connections.

Full SSL verification (most secure):
Download the Supabase CA cert: Dashboard → Database → Settings → Download Certificate
Then in your connection string: sslmode=verify-full&sslrootcert=/path/to/supabase.crt
```

**3. Set up Network Restrictions**
```
Dashboard → Database → Network → Network Restrictions → Add restriction

Add IPs for:
- Your developers' IP addresses
- Your CI/CD server IP (GitHub Actions, etc.)
- Netlify outbound IP ranges (or use Supavisor port 6543 — bypasses network restrictions)

Note: Network Restrictions apply to direct Postgres connections (port 5432/6543).
      supabase-js REST API is NOT affected by network restrictions.
```

**4. Enable MFA on your Supabase account**
```
supabase.com/dashboard → Account → Security → Enable MFA
Your Supabase account has admin access to ALL your projects.
A compromised Supabase account = all projects exposed.
```

**5. Rotate API keys if exposed**
```
If any key was accidentally committed to git or exposed in logs:
Dashboard → Settings → API → Revoke and regenerate immediately.
Then update all .env files and Netlify environment variables.
```

---

### Authentication (must complete)

**6. Switch to custom SMTP before launch**
```
Default Supabase emails: shared domain, goes to spam, rate limited to 30/hour.
Dashboard → Auth → SMTP Settings → Enable custom SMTP
Use Resend (recommended) — see rocket-supabase-auth-config.mdc for setup.

Rate limits on default SMTP:
  30 auth emails/hour (all users combined)
  If exceeded: users cannot receive magic links, confirmations, password resets
```

**7. Fix enterprise email scanner trap** *(for B2B apps)*
```
Problem: Enterprise email security tools (Barracuda, Proofpoint, Mimecast) make GET
requests to every URL in an email to scan for phishing. Since Supabase magic links and
confirmation links are SINGLE-USE, the scanner click expires the link before the user reads it.
User clicks the link → "Link is invalid or has expired."

This affects: magic link login, email confirmation, password reset emails.
It affects all B2B Rocket apps where users have corporate email.
```

```html
<!-- Fix: email template that uses a button, not a direct link -->
<!-- Dashboard → Auth → Email Templates → [Confirm signup / Magic Link] -->
<!-- Replace the direct ConfirmationURL link with a landing page approach: -->

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<body style="font-family: sans-serif; max-width: 600px; margin: 40px auto; padding: 20px;">
  <h2>Confirm your account</h2>
  <p>Click the button below to confirm. This link expires in 1 hour.</p>

  <!-- Button opens a page — scanner only sees the page URL, not the Supabase link -->
  <a href="{{ .SiteURL }}/auth/confirm?token_hash={{ .TokenHash }}&type=email"
     style="background:#1a1a1a;color:white;padding:12px 24px;text-decoration:none;
            border-radius:6px;display:inline-block;margin:20px 0;">
    Confirm my account
  </a>

  <p style="color:#999;font-size:13px;">If you didn't request this, ignore this email.</p>
</body>
</html>
```

```typescript
// app/auth/confirm/page.tsx — landing page with confirm button
// Scanner sees this page (no side effects), user clicks button to actually confirm
'use client'
import { useState } from 'react'
import { useSearchParams, useRouter } from 'next/navigation'
import { createClient } from '@/lib/supabase/client'

export default function ConfirmPage() {
  const [confirming, setConfirming] = useState(false)
  const searchParams = useSearchParams()
  const router = useRouter()
  const supabase = createClient()

  const confirm = async () => {
    setConfirming(true)
    const token_hash = searchParams.get('token_hash')
    const type = searchParams.get('type') as any

    const { error } = await supabase.auth.verifyOtp({ token_hash, type })
    if (error) {
      alert('Link expired or invalid. Please request a new one.')
    } else {
      router.push('/')
    }
    setConfirming(false)
  }

  return (
    <div style={{ textAlign: 'center', marginTop: '10rem' }}>
      <h2>Confirm your account</h2>
      <button onClick={confirm} disabled={confirming}>
        {confirming ? 'Confirming...' : 'Confirm my account'}
      </button>
    </div>
  )
}
```

**8. Verify all redirect URLs are set**
```
Dashboard → Auth → URL Configuration
Must include:
  https://yourdomain.com/**
  https://yourdomain.netlify.app/**
  https://*.netlify.app/**   (for preview deploys)
  http://localhost:3000/**   (for local dev)

Set Site URL to your production domain (not localhost).
```

